{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17513729","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17513729"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:13:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:13:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12200"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12200","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12200"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.27,0.09,0.58,0.05,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4728"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114977"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4728","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4728"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12200"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96983"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1366"},{"type":"tags","id":"2955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7456"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9014"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11359"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11391"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43301"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48608"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114977","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114977"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to her GP with a two-month history of polydipsia, polyuria and nocturia. She reports feeling distressed, as her excessive urination persists despite her efforts to restrict water intake. She has a long-standing history of hypertension, hyperlipidaemia, depression and bipolar affective disorder. Her current medications include candesartan, atorvastatin and lithium for the past 15 years. On examination, her heart rate is 90/min and blood pressure is 110/70 mmHg, she also appears lethargic and euvolaemic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELaboratory results are as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum Na+: 150 mEq/L (135-145)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum osmolality: 305 mOsmol/kg (270-295)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrine osmolality: 450 mOsmol/kg (500-850)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient is referred to nephrology and psychiatry and undergoes further testing and evaluation. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is likely to be the most appropriate treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Immediate desmopressin administration","Thiazide diuretics","Reduction/ discontinuation of lithium","Water restriction","Urea tablets"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EBased on the patient\u0027s clinical presentation and laboratory results, it appears that she is likely suffering from lithium-induced nephrogenic diabetes insipidus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDiabetes insipidus is characterised by an inability to concentrate urine, which can be caused by a deficiency of ADH (central cause) or a resistance to its action at the level of the renal tubule (peripheral). The laboratory findings of hypertonic hypernatraemia and low urine osmolality and specific gravity are consistent with diabetes insipidus. To diagnose diabetes insipidus and differentiate between a central and nephrogenic cause, a water deprivation test and a desmopressin administration test may be performed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s history of long-term lithium supports this diagnosis. Lithium affects the response of renal tubules to ADH by inhibiting the signalling pathway at cytotoxic concentrations, leading to dysfunction of the aquaporin-2 water channel. As a result, patients with this condition typically experience polyuria, polydipsia, and nocturia. The amount of urine passed can range from 3 to more than 20 litres in a day. Notably, significant nocturia is a common presenting feature, and its absence would make diabetes insipidus less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA reduction or discontinuation of lithium\u003C/strong\u003E is likely to be necessary in this case, given it is the presumed cause of this patient\u0027s diabetes insipidus. However, stopping lithium abruptly may be life-threatening and precipitate relapse of bipolar disorder if not carefully managed, and should only be done rapidly if there is significant acute renal failure or lithium toxicity. The decision should be made in close liaison with psychiatry after weighing up risks/benefits in the context of their psychiatric history. There is some evidence that dose reduction can be enough to resolve mild nephrogenic diabetes insipidus. If a decision was made to stop, the patient should be weaned off and changed to an alternative mood-stabilising agent (such as an atypical antipsychotic).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmediate desmopressin administration\u003C/strong\u003E may be useful in cases of central diabetes insipidus, where there is a deficiency of ADH. However, in nephrogenic diabetes insipidus, such as this patient\u0027s case, desmopressin would not be effective as there is resistance to ADH in the renal tubules, and desmopressin is a synthetic analogue of ADH.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThiazide diuretics\u003C/strong\u003E can paradoxically improve urine concentrating ability in some patients with nephrogenic diabetes insipidus by inducing mild volume depletion and increasing proximal tubular sodium reabsorption. However, this approach is not the primary treatment option for this patient, as lithium is the cause and should be discontinued first.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate treatment option for this patient would be to \u003Cstrong\u003Ediscontinue lithium use\u003C/strong\u003E, as it will reverse the underlying cause of the patient\u0027s symptoms. If dehydration is present, IV fluid replacement can be given, not lowering the osmolality too low, as this may precipitate neurological injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWater restriction \u003C/strong\u003Eis not a recommended treatment for this patient. This treatment may be done in the management of Syndrome of Inappropriate Antidiuretic Hormone Secretion (SIADH), which is characterised by excessive ADH secretion leading to water retention and hyponatremia. It may also be recommended for primary polydipsia, which can present similarly, although it commonly demonstrates hypotonic hyponatremia and would be a far less likely diagnosis than nephrogenic diabetes inspidus, given the history of lithium use. This vignette is suggestive of nephrogenic diabetes insipidus, and water restriction would further concentrate the blood, leading to severe hypernatremia, which can be incredibly dangerous.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrea tablets\u003C/strong\u003E\u00a0can also be used in cases of SIADH; similarly, however, these will also increase serum osmolality and are likely to exacerbate the clinical scenario.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Lithium is the most common cause of drug-induced nephrogenic diabetes insipidus","Diabetes insipidus is characterised by polyuria, nocturia, polydipsia, and laboratory findings of plasma hyperosmolarity, and decreased urine osmolarity and specific gravity"],"references":["Bockenhauer D, Bichet DG. Pathophysiology, diagnosis and management of nephrogenic diabetes insipidus. Nature Reviews Nephrology [Internet]. 2015 Jun 16 [cited 2023 May 8];11(10):576\u201388. Available from: https://www.nature.com/articles/nrneph.2015.89","Christ-Crain M, Bichet DG, Fenske WK, Goldman MB, Rittig S, Verbalis JG, et al. Diabetes insipidus. Nature Reviews Disease Primers [Internet]. 2019 Aug 8 [cited 2023 May 8];5(1). Available from: https://www.nature.com/articles/s41572-019-0103-2","Gr\u00fcnfeld JP, Rossier BC. Lithium nephrotoxicity revisited. Nature Reviews Nephrology [Internet]. 2009 May [cited 2023 May 8];5(5):270\u20136. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19384328/",""]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96983"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12200"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96983","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96983"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-21T18:02:38+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-21T18:03:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4728"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114977"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","na